  "prompt": "What is the best closing lines of TV/film?",
  "response": "The \"best\" closing lines of TV or film often depend on personal taste, but here are some iconic and memorable ones that have left a lasting impact:\n\n1. **\"The Godfather\" (1972)**  \n   Michael Corleone: \"Don\u2019t ask me about my business, Kay.\"  \n   *The chilling finality of Michael\u2019s transformation into the Don.*\n\n2. **\"The Usual Suspects\" (1995)**  \n   Verbal Kint: \"And like that... he\u2019s gone.\"  \n   *A jaw-dropping reveal and closing line that redefines the entire film.*\n\n3. **\"Fight Club\" (1999)**  \n   Narrator: \"You met me at a very strange time in my life.\"  \n   *A poignant and ambiguous ending as destruction unfolds.*\n\n4. **\"The Dark Knight\" (2008)**  \n   Commissioner Gordon: \"Because he's the hero Gotham deserves, but not the one it needs right now. So we'll hunt him. Because he can take it. Because he's not our hero. He's a silent guardian, a watchful protector. A dark knight.\"  \n   *A poetic summation of Batman\u2019s sacrifice.*\n\n5. **\"Casabl\"anca\" (1942)**  \n   Captain Renault: \"Louis, I think this is the beginning of a beautiful friendship.\"  \n   *A bittersweet and hopeful note after Rick\u2019s act of selflessness.*\n\n6. **\"The Sopranos\" (2007)**  \n   *Cut to black* followed by: \"Don\u2019t Stop Believin\u2019\"  \n   *Though not a line, the abrupt ending left audiences debating its meaning for years.*\n\n7. **\"The Truman Show\" (1998)**  \n   Truman: \"In case I don\u2019t see ya, good afternoon, good evening, and good night!\"  \n   *A triumphant and defiant exit from the staged world.*\n\n8. **\"Inception\" (2010)**  \n   *The spinning top wobbles* followed by cut to black.  \n   *A cliffhanger that leaves audiences questioning reality.*\n\n9. **\"Breaking Bad\" (2013)**  \n   Walter White: \"I did it for me. I liked it. I was good at it. And I was\u2026 really\u2026 I was alive.\"  \n   *A brutally honest admission of Walter\u2019s true motivations.*\n\n10. **\"Good Will Hunting\" (1997)**  \n    Will: \"Son of a bitch. He stole my line.\"  \n    *A lighthearted and heartwarming conclusion to Will\u2019s journey.*\n\nThese closing lines (or moments) resonate because they often encapsulate the themes, emotions, or revelations of the story, leaving audiences with a powerful final impression.",
